00:01:34.910 --> 00:01:37.510
Let's go into the
game play aspect more.

00:01:37.510 --> 00:01:39.680
So Poker Stars created
this private league for us,

00:01:39.680 --> 00:01:40.780
which is really cool.

00:01:40.780 --> 00:01:45.870
So Poker Stars is generally
considered the most reputable

00:01:45.870 --> 00:01:47.160
online poker site.

00:01:47.160 --> 00:01:48.520
That's why we use them.

00:01:48.520 --> 00:01:50.725
So they have two
different types of games.

00:01:50.725 --> 00:01:52.600
So they have real money
and play money games.

00:01:52.600 --> 00:01:57.540
Now if you're in the US,
you can't do real money.

00:01:57.540 --> 00:01:59.565
It used to be something
that was very gray area.

00:02:02.480 --> 00:02:05.130
And then there was one
poker site which turned out

00:02:05.130 --> 00:02:10.720
to be legitimately like a
Ponzi scheme, and as a result,

00:02:10.720 --> 00:02:15.260
now poker in the US is like
much more black and white,

00:02:15.260 --> 00:02:17.220
definitely not OK
for real money.

00:02:17.220 --> 00:02:20.050
However, their play money
scene is pretty resilient,

00:02:20.050 --> 00:02:22.102
and that's what we're
taking advantage of here.

00:02:22.102 --> 00:02:24.060
The Poker Stars play
money scene is broken down

00:02:24.060 --> 00:02:25.290
into two different things.

00:02:25.290 --> 00:02:29.340
They have public games, where
you can just go and play

00:02:29.340 --> 00:02:33.950
for play chips against anyone
in the world, which is cool.

00:02:33.950 --> 00:02:35.690
And you can do that,
and I recommend

00:02:35.690 --> 00:02:38.469
you give it a shot just to
get used to the software.

00:02:38.469 --> 00:02:40.010
In addition, you
could do home games,

00:02:40.010 --> 00:02:42.410
which is what we're
generally going to be doing.

00:02:42.410 --> 00:02:46.650
That's what they call
their private leagues.

00:02:46.650 --> 00:02:50.230
So in the private leagues,
in their home games,

00:02:50.230 --> 00:02:51.700
they have this showcase.

00:02:51.700 --> 00:02:54.090
And you might notice
as soon as you log in

00:02:54.090 --> 00:02:56.210
that the MIT League, Poker
Theory and Analytics,

00:02:56.210 --> 00:02:57.570
is already at the top.

00:02:57.570 --> 00:02:58.650
That's not just for us.

00:02:58.650 --> 00:02:59.950
That's for everyone.

00:02:59.950 --> 00:03:02.630
Anyone in the world who
logs into Poker Stars

00:03:02.630 --> 00:03:05.080
and looks at home games
has the MIT League

00:03:05.080 --> 00:03:07.530
at the top, which I
think is really cool.

00:03:07.530 --> 00:03:09.910
So to access this, I'll send
a more specific instructions

00:03:09.910 --> 00:03:10.410
later.

00:03:10.410 --> 00:03:13.904
I gave you guys just the
passcode of what you need.

00:03:13.904 --> 00:03:15.820
But to actually get
there, what you need to do

00:03:15.820 --> 00:03:17.610
is, you log into Poker Stars.

00:03:17.610 --> 00:03:21.120
You go to this button,
which is a little house,

00:03:21.120 --> 00:03:22.490
to access home games.

00:03:22.490 --> 00:03:24.560
And then you want
to join a game.

00:03:24.560 --> 00:03:29.376
And what you do is, you put
the Club ID, which is 557832.

00:03:29.376 --> 00:03:31.250
You put the invitation
code, which you're all

00:03:31.250 --> 00:03:32.690
going to have on Stellar.

00:03:32.690 --> 00:03:35.860
And then you put your real
name, preferably the one that's

00:03:35.860 --> 00:03:37.600
listed in the course,
because I actually

00:03:37.600 --> 00:03:39.910
have to approve everyone
that joins the league,

00:03:39.910 --> 00:03:42.470
and I can't do it just based
on someone's screen name.

00:03:42.470 --> 00:03:44.594
And I guess you have to
agree to some sort of terms

00:03:44.594 --> 00:03:45.470
and conditions.

00:03:45.470 --> 00:03:46.930
So let's talk
about hand history.

00:03:46.930 --> 00:03:49.100
So a lot of analytics
are going to be based off

00:03:49.100 --> 00:03:53.470
of hand histories, which are
just text files that Poker

00:03:53.470 --> 00:03:58.830
Stars gives you to the extent
that you indicate that you want

00:03:58.830 --> 00:04:00.060
to save them down.

00:04:00.060 --> 00:04:03.030
So these are kind of
jumbled messes of text.

00:04:03.030 --> 00:04:05.110
Each line just shows
one thing that happens.

00:04:05.110 --> 00:04:07.110
And you might get
used to reading it,

00:04:07.110 --> 00:04:09.691
or might not,
depending on how much

00:04:09.691 --> 00:04:10.940
you're going to scrutinize it.

00:04:10.940 --> 00:04:12.450
But more importantly,
you can use

00:04:12.450 --> 00:04:15.320
these in all the data
analytic programs

00:04:15.320 --> 00:04:16.589
that we're going to use.

00:04:16.589 --> 00:04:19.550
In particular, Poker
Tracker runs off of that.

00:04:19.550 --> 00:04:24.770
You'll load just thousands
of hands into Poker Tracker,

00:04:24.770 --> 00:04:26.400
and it'll do analytics for you.

00:04:26.400 --> 00:04:29.540
It knows exactly what's going on
based on that format, which is

00:04:29.540 --> 00:04:31.390
generally considered universal.

00:04:31.390 --> 00:04:35.805
And then for the sake of
visualizing these hands--

00:04:35.805 --> 00:04:37.180
if you just read
it, that's fine.

00:04:37.180 --> 00:04:39.170
But then if you want
to show other people,

00:04:39.170 --> 00:04:41.420
I'm recommending we use
something called the Universal

00:04:41.420 --> 00:04:44.360
Hand History Replayer, which
is something that's free.

00:04:44.360 --> 00:04:47.950
And what it does, it just reads
the hands, and it plays them.

00:04:47.950 --> 00:04:50.940
It animates what happened as
if you were seeing it for real.

00:04:50.940 --> 00:04:52.430
So the deal with
hand histories is,

00:04:52.430 --> 00:04:57.080
if you're a real money player,
Poker Stars dedicates databases

00:04:57.080 --> 00:05:00.440
of hand histories so
that, if you want,

00:05:00.440 --> 00:05:03.810
you can request all your
hand histories at any time.

00:05:03.810 --> 00:05:09.520
For play money players, they
let you capture your own hand

00:05:09.520 --> 00:05:13.200
histories if you want, but they
definitely don't save them.

00:05:13.200 --> 00:05:15.369
So the reason I'm
showing you this now,

00:05:15.369 --> 00:05:17.160
and I'm going to email
it out to you later,

00:05:17.160 --> 00:05:19.520
is if you lose your
hand histories,

00:05:19.520 --> 00:05:21.300
so you don't capture
them in time,

00:05:21.300 --> 00:05:23.340
you'll never get them back.

00:05:23.340 --> 00:05:26.967
So make sure you're actually
capturing hand histories,

00:05:26.967 --> 00:05:29.550
because we're going to be using
that for a lot of the analysis

00:05:29.550 --> 00:05:31.212
we do.

00:05:31.212 --> 00:05:32.670
OK, so let's talk
about the league.

00:05:32.670 --> 00:05:34.530
And honestly, I
think this league

00:05:34.530 --> 00:05:36.000
is going to be really cool.

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:39.450
Usually the
evolution of a player

00:05:39.450 --> 00:05:42.310
is they're terrible at
poker, and then they

00:05:42.310 --> 00:05:45.250
start becoming good at
playing against bad people.

00:05:45.250 --> 00:05:47.817
And then when they actually
start playing for real,

00:05:47.817 --> 00:05:49.400
they get crushed
again because they're

00:05:49.400 --> 00:05:52.160
used to playing against
other bad people.

00:05:52.160 --> 00:05:54.610
So this will actually
hopefully get

00:05:54.610 --> 00:05:57.330
you used to playing
against other people who

00:05:57.330 --> 00:06:01.110
are playing correctly, which is
not something you can commonly

00:06:01.110 --> 00:06:06.480
learn just from playing
around with your friends.

00:06:06.480 --> 00:06:10.980
In addition through playing
in these online leagues,

00:06:10.980 --> 00:06:14.020
you can collect stats
that you could never

00:06:14.020 --> 00:06:15.410
get from playing live.

00:06:15.410 --> 00:06:22.030
And I think this is why the
live tournament scene is

00:06:22.030 --> 00:06:24.140
dominated by online pros.

00:06:24.140 --> 00:06:30.230
It's because no live pro
can get as many hands

00:06:30.230 --> 00:06:34.350
or analyze their play in the
way that you can do online.

00:06:34.350 --> 00:06:35.980
It's not even comparable.

00:06:35.980 --> 00:06:41.500
So this is given-- even if your
whole intention is to only play

00:06:41.500 --> 00:06:45.330
live the entire rest your life,
doing this type of analytics

00:06:45.330 --> 00:06:48.380
would give you a chance to
learn at a much faster rate

00:06:48.380 --> 00:06:51.530
and learn things that
you would never see live.

00:06:51.530 --> 00:06:57.020
So every week we're going to
have a major tournament, which

00:06:57.020 --> 00:06:59.450
is basically going to be
the same structure, maybe

00:06:59.450 --> 00:07:02.250
a little bit slower, than
the ones we do daily,

00:07:02.250 --> 00:07:04.470
except they're going
to have real prizes.

00:07:04.470 --> 00:07:08.970
So Akuna is giving us, for
their first tournament,

00:07:08.970 --> 00:07:10.270
Beats headphones.

00:07:10.270 --> 00:07:15.250
And Apple TV, Bose speakers
and a lot of gift cards.

00:07:15.250 --> 00:07:16.800
And then for their
second tournament,

00:07:16.800 --> 00:07:19.770
they're giving us
all of those things

00:07:19.770 --> 00:07:23.430
plus an iPad Air
and an iPad Mini.

00:07:23.430 --> 00:07:26.650
But we're not done yet.

00:07:26.650 --> 00:07:29.480
Because this class is
focused on playing live,

00:07:29.480 --> 00:07:32.130
we're going to end the
class with a live tournament

00:07:32.130 --> 00:07:34.940
sponsored by Optiver
on the 31st, which

00:07:34.940 --> 00:07:37.240
is the day after the
last day of the class.

00:07:37.240 --> 00:07:38.990
So after the league's
over, and after you

00:07:38.990 --> 00:07:42.430
guys are good at poker,
you'll have an opportunity

00:07:42.430 --> 00:07:47.080
to play each other in a live
tournament, where their prize

00:07:47.080 --> 00:07:51.740
pool is all of the Akuna
prizes, plus a PlayStation

00:07:51.740 --> 00:07:56.300
4, plus an iPad, plus a
Kindle, and plus a GoPro.

00:07:56.300 --> 00:08:03.430
I want this to reflect
the type of things

00:08:03.430 --> 00:08:06.830
an online, multi-table
tournament player would do.

00:08:06.830 --> 00:08:10.810
How it normally works is,
during the week, and basically

00:08:10.810 --> 00:08:13.300
every single day, there
is a uniform amount

00:08:13.300 --> 00:08:15.810
of tournaments that will
just run every single day

00:08:15.810 --> 00:08:17.320
at the top of the hour.

00:08:17.320 --> 00:08:20.240
And these pros will
just grind those out.

00:08:20.240 --> 00:08:21.660
They'll get used
to the structure.

00:08:21.660 --> 00:08:25.930
And that's where they'll
kind of grind their teeth.

00:08:25.930 --> 00:08:28.120
And then on the
weekends, that's when

00:08:28.120 --> 00:08:34.390
you get a lot of the square
money, a lot of the newer guys

00:08:34.390 --> 00:08:36.240
who only play poker
on the weekend.

00:08:36.240 --> 00:08:39.690
And those are more gimmicky,
idiosyncratic tournaments,

00:08:39.690 --> 00:08:41.940
but also the highest value.

00:08:41.940 --> 00:08:46.650
So that's why I'm producing the
tournament structure like this,

00:08:46.650 --> 00:08:48.360
where the bulk of
your tournaments

00:08:48.360 --> 00:08:50.980
will be very similar
to each other.

00:08:50.980 --> 00:08:53.060
But then the tournaments
that really matter

00:08:53.060 --> 00:08:56.712
will be completely different,
at least relatively different.

00:08:56.712 --> 00:08:57.920
So that's why I'm doing that.

00:08:57.920 --> 00:08:59.870
That'll make you
get a feel for what

00:08:59.870 --> 00:09:01.590
these guys have to go through.

00:09:01.590 --> 00:09:03.520
So let's talk about turbos.

00:09:03.520 --> 00:09:09.340
Turbos let you focus on
pre-flop decisions, which

00:09:09.340 --> 00:09:12.020
are the area where I
think there is the most

00:09:12.020 --> 00:09:16.360
to learn among people
who are new at poker.

00:09:16.360 --> 00:09:18.680
Basically, all of
your value that you're

00:09:18.680 --> 00:09:21.320
losing in tournament is
from screwing up pre-flop.

00:09:21.320 --> 00:09:24.950
No one gets that right live
because it's really difficult

00:09:24.950 --> 00:09:29.320
to be able to feel comfortable
doing what's generally

00:09:29.320 --> 00:09:30.150
considered right.

00:09:30.150 --> 00:09:32.570
And we're going to spend
a lot of time on pre-flop.

00:09:32.570 --> 00:09:35.250
But these turbos encourage
you to do that sort of thing,

00:09:35.250 --> 00:09:37.300
because live is a
lot of pre-flop,

00:09:37.300 --> 00:09:40.810
and you're going to be doing
that in the turbos online, too.

00:09:40.810 --> 00:09:42.840
In addition, no
one wants to spend

00:09:42.840 --> 00:09:44.580
six hours doing a tournament.

00:09:44.580 --> 00:09:46.290
So I'm making these
turbos so you can

00:09:46.290 --> 00:09:48.440
be in and out in 45 minutes.

00:09:48.440 --> 00:09:50.300
And then you boot up
another tournament,

00:09:50.300 --> 00:09:54.620
or you can be done with
poker for that night.

00:09:54.620 --> 00:09:56.890
In addition, you have
the opportunity--

00:09:56.890 --> 00:09:58.770
you can play as many
tournaments as you want.

00:09:58.770 --> 00:10:01.880
It's common for pros to do
something called multi-tabling

00:10:01.880 --> 00:10:06.900
which is they'll do multiple
tournaments at the same time.

00:10:06.900 --> 00:10:10.150
For the beginners, I'd probably
recommend you just do one.

00:10:10.150 --> 00:10:13.090
But for the regular
league, have at that.

00:10:13.090 --> 00:10:16.290
you want to do like all four
tournaments at the same time,

00:10:16.290 --> 00:10:18.450
go ahead, to the extent
that they overlap

00:10:18.450 --> 00:10:20.410
with each other a little bit.

00:10:20.410 --> 00:10:20.910
OK.

00:10:20.910 --> 00:10:22.576
So that's the end
with the prize league.

00:10:22.576 --> 00:10:25.890
So the schedule is, we're
going to go through what

00:10:25.890 --> 00:10:28.390
I'm calling basic
strategy, which

00:10:28.390 --> 00:10:35.270
are the basic axioms that we're
going to be using in order

00:10:35.270 --> 00:10:40.122
to analyze the decision
making process in poker.

00:10:40.122 --> 00:10:42.080
Then we're going to be
doing pre-flop analysis.

00:10:42.080 --> 00:10:44.690
And we're going to be doing
a lot of this, because this

00:10:44.690 --> 00:10:48.930
is really where the
value add is going to be,

00:10:48.930 --> 00:10:51.080
is getting this right.

00:10:51.080 --> 00:10:54.750
I think the way
that we can tackle

00:10:54.750 --> 00:10:57.460
this thing is kind of a
way I recommend that you

00:10:57.460 --> 00:10:59.370
learn anything complicated.

00:10:59.370 --> 00:11:03.450
So we're going to
break this down

00:11:03.450 --> 00:11:06.140
into three different sections.

00:11:06.140 --> 00:11:10.220
Fundamental concept, practice,
which are actually implementing

00:11:10.220 --> 00:11:14.610
those concepts when you have
10 seconds to make a decision,

00:11:14.610 --> 00:11:17.240
and then more advanced stuff.

00:11:17.240 --> 00:11:20.550
With regard to
concepts, I'm going

00:11:20.550 --> 00:11:23.080
to call this the basic
framework for decision making.

00:11:23.080 --> 00:11:25.250
It's being unexploitable.

00:11:25.250 --> 00:11:28.870
You want to get to the level
when you sit down at a table,

00:11:28.870 --> 00:11:30.960
every pro in the room
doesn't turn and go,

00:11:30.960 --> 00:11:32.830
I want to sit at
that guy's table.

00:11:32.830 --> 00:11:35.590
You want to be a
slightly winning player

00:11:35.590 --> 00:11:39.240
way before you want to
become a huge winning player.

00:11:39.240 --> 00:11:42.200
In order to let you
know the type of thing

00:11:42.200 --> 00:11:46.750
that we're learning, I'm going
to label the slides with this,

00:11:46.750 --> 00:11:50.000
to indicate that this
is like a basic concept.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:54.200
Learn this thing
before you move on.

00:11:54.200 --> 00:11:58.260
The advanced stuff
is, once you learn

00:11:58.260 --> 00:12:03.660
how to do things-- which how
to do things is pretty broad--

00:12:03.660 --> 00:12:07.040
we're going to learn minor
adjustments that we can do

00:12:07.040 --> 00:12:10.690
to get quite a bit
of extra money,

00:12:10.690 --> 00:12:14.700
like how to grind out that
additional half big blind

00:12:14.700 --> 00:12:16.710
an hour out of our opponents.

00:12:20.380 --> 00:12:22.990
So any real deviations
from what we normally

00:12:22.990 --> 00:12:25.680
do, in addition to meta game.

00:12:25.680 --> 00:12:27.810
Meta game is always
fun, like anything

00:12:27.810 --> 00:12:30.950
not related to the
hand to hand decision

00:12:30.950 --> 00:12:32.940
making process, like
table selection,

00:12:32.940 --> 00:12:37.100
or bankroll
management, or deciding

00:12:37.100 --> 00:12:38.510
whether or not to play.

00:12:38.510 --> 00:12:40.010
That stuff is really
fun, and that's

00:12:40.010 --> 00:12:42.001
to be indicated
by this ace here.

00:12:42.001 --> 00:12:42.500
OK.

00:12:42.500 --> 00:12:45.290
So I'm going to label those
slides for anything that's

00:12:45.290 --> 00:12:48.320
considered advanced, and stuff
you should only really do

00:12:48.320 --> 00:12:50.511
when you get the concepts down.

00:12:50.511 --> 00:12:52.052
And then a lot of
this class is going

00:12:52.052 --> 00:12:58.700
to be focused on practice, which
is how to actually implement

00:12:58.700 --> 00:13:02.700
these concepts on a day to
