00:17:04.800 --> 00:17:06.400
So let's move on to a concept.

00:17:06.400 --> 00:17:07.400
So stack size.

00:17:07.400 --> 00:17:09.349
So this might seem
fairly simple,

00:17:09.349 --> 00:17:12.240
but we ought to make sure we're
talking about the same thing

00:17:12.240 --> 00:17:13.660
when we go through this.

00:17:13.660 --> 00:17:17.520
So your stack size,
it's the value

00:17:17.520 --> 00:17:19.200
of the chips in front of you.

00:17:19.200 --> 00:17:21.066
So that's fairly normal.

00:17:21.066 --> 00:17:23.440
But we have this thing called
effective stack size, which

00:17:23.440 --> 00:17:25.981
is what we're usually going to
be talking about when we refer

00:17:25.981 --> 00:17:31.320
to stack, which is the
minimum of your stack

00:17:31.320 --> 00:17:34.330
or the next biggest
stack after you.

00:17:34.330 --> 00:17:36.610
And the way to
think about this is

00:17:36.610 --> 00:17:41.680
the number of chips you could
possibly lose in this one hand.

00:17:41.680 --> 00:17:44.200
That's what your
relevant stack size is.

00:17:44.200 --> 00:17:48.640
And the way you make decisions
will depend on your effective

00:17:48.640 --> 00:17:50.530
stack much more
than anything else.

00:17:50.530 --> 00:17:53.805
So an example of
this would be, say

00:17:53.805 --> 00:18:01.650
you're in a heads up situation
where you're the hero here

00:18:01.650 --> 00:18:03.700
on the small blind.

00:18:03.700 --> 00:18:07.580
Big blind has,
whatever, 300 chips.

00:18:07.580 --> 00:18:10.940
And you have some amount
of chips with queens.

00:18:17.520 --> 00:18:19.800
So if you have 1,500
chips, and so does

00:18:19.800 --> 00:18:32.270
he-- say blinds are like 10/20--
you have, what, like 50 times

00:18:32.270 --> 00:18:33.880
the blinds combined here.

00:18:33.880 --> 00:18:37.780
So this is a pretty
different hand than aces.

00:18:37.780 --> 00:18:39.740
Why?

00:18:39.740 --> 00:18:44.090
So say that you raise with
queens, and then he raises you.

00:18:44.090 --> 00:18:48.375
So you raise to 60, he raises
you to 200, you raise to 600,

00:18:48.375 --> 00:18:51.850
and he pushes to 1,500.

00:18:51.850 --> 00:18:55.030
Your queens are probably not
really that good anymore.

00:18:55.030 --> 00:18:56.830
It matters how many
chips you have here.

00:18:56.830 --> 00:19:04.170
However, if you have 300
chips, you raise with queens,

00:19:04.170 --> 00:19:06.810
and then he pushes over,
you can't fold that.

00:19:06.810 --> 00:19:11.220
You might as well have aces,
and it makes your hands,

00:19:11.220 --> 00:19:13.770
the way you play hands,
materially different.

00:19:13.770 --> 00:19:15.970
That's why chip size
matters in general.

00:19:15.970 --> 00:19:18.840
When the chip stack
is low, you're

00:19:18.840 --> 00:19:21.500
playing these two hands
basically identical.

00:19:21.500 --> 00:19:24.850
You're saying-- you're
just playing this range.

00:19:24.850 --> 00:19:28.660
However, when we're talking
about effective chip stack,

00:19:28.660 --> 00:19:35.050
it's the same thing, where
even if you have 1,500

00:19:35.050 --> 00:19:39.667
and he has 300, if you
raise, he's going to push.

00:19:39.667 --> 00:19:42.000
You don't have the opportunity
to do that back and forth

00:19:42.000 --> 00:19:42.720
anymore.

00:19:42.720 --> 00:19:46.000
So you might as well
have 300 with regard

00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:47.590
to your decision making here.

00:19:47.590 --> 00:19:49.640
That's why we're looking
at the effective stack,

00:19:49.640 --> 00:19:53.010
because it really matters who
has the least number of chips,

00:19:53.010 --> 00:19:55.510
because that determines when
the action is going to be over.

00:19:59.650 --> 00:20:01.885
So really, I like this
definition the most,

00:20:01.885 --> 00:20:04.670
the most amount of chips that
you can lose in the hand.

00:20:04.670 --> 00:20:08.430
It's a lot more, I think,
simple to think about

00:20:08.430 --> 00:20:10.970
than this min formula.

00:20:10.970 --> 00:20:11.470
OK.

00:20:11.470 --> 00:20:14.097
And then we're almost always
talking about effective stack.

00:20:14.097 --> 00:20:15.430
Let's talk about Dan Harrington.

00:20:15.430 --> 00:20:23.890
So Dan Harrington is a player
whose style I very much like.

00:20:23.890 --> 00:20:28.280
His nickname's Action
Dan, which the consensus

00:20:28.280 --> 00:20:31.640
is, he just kind of gave
himself, because he's

00:20:31.640 --> 00:20:37.620
considered Mr. Fundamental, like
tight aggressive ABC player.

00:20:37.620 --> 00:20:41.480
So this playing style, this
temperament, tight aggressive,

00:20:41.480 --> 00:20:48.050
is something that is used to
characterize basic playing

00:20:48.050 --> 00:20:49.050
styles.

00:20:49.050 --> 00:20:51.200
So let's quickly go
through what those are.

00:20:51.200 --> 00:20:55.100
So there are two
different axes here.

00:20:55.100 --> 00:20:59.020
There's how often
you bet, where bet

00:20:59.020 --> 00:21:00.970
means you are
raising the stakes,

00:21:00.970 --> 00:21:03.490
so either you bet or you raise.

00:21:03.490 --> 00:21:05.920
And then here's
how often you call.

00:21:05.920 --> 00:21:09.110
Either you call a lot or
you call not that much.

00:21:09.110 --> 00:21:12.360
You can get a good feel for
the type of person someone

00:21:12.360 --> 00:21:14.957
is by what box they fill in.

00:21:14.957 --> 00:21:15.790
So these have names.

00:21:15.790 --> 00:21:17.900
So someone who's
tight aggressive,

00:21:17.900 --> 00:21:20.110
you would just refer
to them as Tag, which

00:21:20.110 --> 00:21:23.520
is like what Dan Harrington is.

00:21:23.520 --> 00:21:27.000
You bet when you have
good hands and you

00:21:27.000 --> 00:21:30.100
fold when you have bad hands.

00:21:30.100 --> 00:21:33.890
Another possibly winning
strategy is loose aggressive,

00:21:33.890 --> 00:21:37.360
Lag, where you certainly bet
when you have good hands,

00:21:37.360 --> 00:21:40.000
but you will see a lot
of cards before you'll

00:21:40.000 --> 00:21:41.100
give up on a hand.

00:21:41.100 --> 00:21:44.810
You're definitely
willing to call a lot.

00:21:44.810 --> 00:21:49.870
These, type passive, are
not pronounceable words,

00:21:49.870 --> 00:21:53.650
so the community generally
came up with different words

00:21:53.650 --> 00:21:54.600
to describe these.

00:21:57.290 --> 00:22:00.710
So a tight passive
person is weak.

00:22:00.710 --> 00:22:03.800
They're someone who you
can completely run over,

00:22:03.800 --> 00:22:06.600
because they fold when
they have a bad hand,

00:22:06.600 --> 00:22:08.505
they check when they
have a good hand.

00:22:11.520 --> 00:22:14.120
I guess they would
be called rocks.

00:22:14.120 --> 00:22:16.750
You never need to worry about
having a big losing night

00:22:16.750 --> 00:22:17.880
against these guys.

00:22:17.880 --> 00:22:19.840
So someone who's type
passive is generally

00:22:19.840 --> 00:22:22.170
considered playing
sub-optionally.

00:22:22.170 --> 00:22:26.100
And then the loose
passive people

00:22:26.100 --> 00:22:31.060
are described-- this icon,
which I forget what it's from.

00:22:31.060 --> 00:22:35.340
I think it might be from an
old version of PokerTracker,

00:22:35.340 --> 00:22:39.140
or maybe it was on Party
Poker or something.

00:22:39.140 --> 00:22:41.900
But everyone loved
seeing this icon which

00:22:41.900 --> 00:22:46.630
you could label people as,
because a loose passive person

00:22:46.630 --> 00:22:48.280
is what?

00:22:48.280 --> 00:22:51.390
They are a calling machine.

00:22:51.390 --> 00:22:53.450
That's what that
stands for, and it

00:22:53.450 --> 00:22:56.820
means that when you
have a hand, they

00:22:56.820 --> 00:22:58.840
will call all of your bets.

00:22:58.840 --> 00:23:01.510
You will extract
value out of them.

00:23:01.510 --> 00:23:04.580
But when they have
a hand, they're

00:23:04.580 --> 00:23:06.520
OK with letting you
look at your draws

00:23:06.520 --> 00:23:10.290
to make a decision about whether
by the river you have a hand

00:23:10.290 --> 00:23:12.300
or not.

00:23:12.300 --> 00:23:16.020
There's virtually no
way that these guys

00:23:16.020 --> 00:23:17.750
are making money in poker.

00:23:17.750 --> 00:23:22.280
I think it would be, like
over a realistic sample size,

00:23:22.280 --> 00:23:26.590
there's no type of player who
could fit in this quadrant

00:23:26.590 --> 00:23:29.640
and be good enough on any
other metric to actually

00:23:29.640 --> 00:23:32.330
be making money in poker.

00:23:32.330 --> 00:23:36.430
So in general how
we look at this is,

00:23:36.430 --> 00:23:40.230
we would call this
Tag guy solid ABC.

00:23:40.230 --> 00:23:42.340
That's what I'm recommending
you guys play as.

00:23:46.050 --> 00:23:49.790
Tag players, as a
quadrant, are going

00:23:49.790 --> 00:23:51.200
to be the biggest winners.

00:23:51.200 --> 00:23:53.180
Lag players, someone
who's very aggressive

00:23:53.180 --> 00:23:56.130
and plays a lot of
hands, could possibly

00:23:56.130 --> 00:23:57.640
be a pretty good winner.

00:24:01.260 --> 00:24:03.880
It depends on the
type of game, and then

00:24:03.880 --> 00:24:06.720
their opponent and their
ability to pick spots.

00:24:06.720 --> 00:24:09.310
But there are a lot
of big Lag winners.

00:24:09.310 --> 00:24:13.050
There are not a lot
of big weak winners.

00:24:13.050 --> 00:24:17.000
And there are not
a lot of calling

00:24:17.000 --> 00:24:21.320
machines, loose passive
players, who are not big losers.

00:24:21.320 --> 00:24:24.520
So anytime you see-- this is
a definition of someone who's

00:24:24.520 --> 00:24:27.460
a complete fish, a huge
donater to the game.

00:24:27.460 --> 00:24:31.210
And your ability to
recognize this type of thing

00:24:31.210 --> 00:24:33.470
will help you find
good games to play,

00:24:33.470 --> 00:24:36.200
when you see someone
doing this kind of thing.

00:24:36.200 --> 00:24:37.780
Anyway, back to Action Dan.

00:24:37.780 --> 00:24:45.480
So Dan Harrington is a
pretty good poker player.

00:24:45.480 --> 00:24:47.050
He's been around the block.

00:24:47.050 --> 00:24:50.400
He won the main event
back in 1995, when it had,

00:24:50.400 --> 00:24:52.060
like, 300 people in it.

00:24:52.060 --> 00:24:57.100
He has two World Series of Poker
bracelets and one World Poker

00:24:57.100 --> 00:24:58.770
Tour title.

00:24:58.770 --> 00:25:00.450
But anyway, so
Harrington popularized

00:25:00.450 --> 00:25:02.100
this thing called
the M-ratio, which

00:25:02.100 --> 00:25:04.760
was invented by someone else.

00:25:04.760 --> 00:25:09.080
So the M-ratio was invented by
this guy Paul Magriel, who's

00:25:09.080 --> 00:25:12.900
a backgammon theorist,
apparently one of the best

00:25:12.900 --> 00:25:15.880
backgammon players in the
world, commentator for the WSOB,

00:25:15.880 --> 00:25:21.910
World Series of Backgammon,
and eight WSOB final tables.

00:25:21.910 --> 00:25:24.220
Anyway, so he's supposedly
really, really good

00:25:24.220 --> 00:25:26.784
at math, even by MIT standards.

00:25:26.784 --> 00:25:28.700
But he invented this
thing called the M-ratio,

00:25:28.700 --> 00:25:30.560
but then it never caught
on until Harrington

00:25:30.560 --> 00:25:31.570
started doing it.

00:25:31.570 --> 00:25:34.360
All right, so
Harrington's M-ratio

00:25:34.360 --> 00:25:39.340
is your effective stack
divided by the sum

00:25:39.340 --> 00:25:41.600
of the blinds and the empties.

00:25:41.600 --> 00:25:43.280
So you'll hear
people talk about,

00:25:43.280 --> 00:25:47.870
like, oh, I had 10 big blinds,
or 15 big blinds or whatever,

00:25:47.870 --> 00:25:49.670
to talk about their chip stack.

00:25:49.670 --> 00:25:53.590
But that has a
fundamental problem.

00:25:53.590 --> 00:25:56.120
It has a lot of
different problems.

00:25:56.120 --> 00:26:02.060
One is, it doesn't
tell the story.

00:26:02.060 --> 00:26:07.300
So the usual blind levels
are like 1/2 or 2/4,

00:26:07.300 --> 00:26:10.570
where the big blind is
just twice the small blind.

00:26:10.570 --> 00:26:12.210
So that's the assumption.

00:26:12.210 --> 00:26:17.390
But if you're at a blind
level that's like 1/3 or 3/5,

00:26:17.390 --> 00:26:19.650
the number of big
blinds you have is not

00:26:19.650 --> 00:26:22.520
indicative of anything.

00:26:22.520 --> 00:26:24.970
It's not indicative of how
many hands you can see,

00:26:24.970 --> 00:26:28.590
or how much you care about
winning a pot pre-flop.

00:26:28.590 --> 00:26:30.610
So using the blinds
is bad, in addition

00:26:30.610 --> 00:26:36.310
to, once you start having,
like, if you're 50/100 blinds

00:26:36.310 --> 00:26:41.650
and you have an ante of 25, you
have basically half the stack

00:26:41.650 --> 00:26:43.960
you had before, in
realistic terms.

00:26:43.960 --> 00:26:47.780
Just to get big blinds doesn't,
in fact, earn antes at all.

00:26:47.780 --> 00:26:52.180
And that's a major problem
referring to it like that.

00:26:52.180 --> 00:26:55.960
So using M seems to
make a lot more sense.

00:26:55.960 --> 00:27:00.200
So what it is, is it's basically
the percentage of your stack

00:27:00.200 --> 00:27:02.430
that is the blinds in the ante.

00:27:02.430 --> 00:27:04.550
So it's like how
many rounds of poker

00:27:04.550 --> 00:27:08.516
you can survive if you just
fold every single hand.

00:27:08.516 --> 00:27:10.140
Of course, you're
not going to do that.

00:27:10.140 --> 00:27:12.490
Although I think that's what
he's actually getting at,

00:27:12.490 --> 00:27:15.270
because he uses M to
refer to when you have

00:27:15.270 --> 00:27:17.750
to make a move, which is not
generally how I recommend

00:27:17.750 --> 00:27:18.780
you do it.

00:27:18.780 --> 00:27:21.320
I think it's more important,
because it means how important

00:27:21.320 --> 00:27:22.740
the blinds are to your stack.

00:27:25.930 --> 00:27:28.410
The only reason anyone
plays any hand of poker

00:27:28.410 --> 00:27:31.410
is because someone
wants to win the blind.

00:27:31.410 --> 00:27:36.040
So even if you have
kings, to some extent,

00:27:36.040 --> 00:27:38.720
if you could win the
blinds, 99% of the time

00:27:38.720 --> 00:27:40.110
you would just do that.

00:27:40.110 --> 00:27:43.100
You don't really all
the time want someone

00:27:43.100 --> 00:27:45.064
to go up against you.

00:27:45.064 --> 00:27:47.230
So the blinds are really
driving the decision making

00:27:47.230 --> 00:27:51.240
process, at least pre-flop.

00:27:51.240 --> 00:27:53.280
And the percentage
that those blinds

00:27:53.280 --> 00:27:55.400
are of your stack matter a lot.

00:27:55.400 --> 00:27:59.520
If they're 1% of your
stack, if your M is 100,

00:27:59.520 --> 00:28:01.390
the blind basically
don't matter at all.

00:28:01.390 --> 00:28:03.680
Whatever happens
after the blinds

00:28:03.680 --> 00:28:06.020
is going to materially
impact your decision.

00:28:06.020 --> 00:28:09.690
Where if your M is 2, and the
blinds are half your stack,

00:28:09.690 --> 00:28:11.327
winning those seems
really important.

00:28:11.327 --> 00:28:13.410
You should do whatever you
can to kind of maximize

00:28:13.410 --> 00:28:14.850
your chance of winning that.

00:28:14.850 --> 00:28:20.710
So that's why M is
a good ratio here.

00:28:20.710 --> 00:28:22.940
And then, in addition,
for tournaments,

00:28:22.940 --> 00:28:28.000
it makes it much easier
to talk about hands

00:28:28.000 --> 00:28:31.220
without having to worry
about all the different parts

00:28:31.220 --> 00:28:33.020
of the tournament life cycle.

00:28:33.020 --> 00:28:37.812
If you have 1,500 chips
and it's 50/100 blinds,

00:28:37.812 --> 00:28:39.520
you can basically make
the same decisions

00:28:39.520 --> 00:28:42.400
as if you have 10 times as
many chips at a level that's

00:28:42.400 --> 00:28:46.494
10 times as high blinds.

00:28:46.494 --> 00:28:47.910
You could just
divide in your head

00:28:47.910 --> 00:28:49.451
and basically make
the same decision.

00:28:49.451 --> 00:28:52.820
You don't need to
worry about doing

00:28:52.820 --> 00:28:56.010
anything different as a
result of having more chips.

00:28:56.010 --> 00:28:58.400
So Harrington
invented or brought up

00:28:58.400 --> 00:29:01.880
a bunch of other things
that never really caught on.

00:29:01.880 --> 00:29:04.380
He invented a thing called
the queue ratio, which

00:29:04.380 --> 00:29:09.510
is your stack size divided
by the average stack size

00:29:09.510 --> 00:29:10.750
in the tournament.

00:29:10.750 --> 00:29:14.500
So I guess you might use this
to get an idea of how far behind

00:29:14.500 --> 00:29:15.910
you are in the tournament.

00:29:15.910 --> 00:29:17.456
Like if your queue
is 5, you don't

00:29:17.456 --> 00:29:18.580
need to be that aggressive.

00:29:18.580 --> 00:29:21.090
But if your queue
is .2, you have

00:29:21.090 --> 00:29:23.340
a lot of catching up to do
before you're realistically

00:29:23.340 --> 00:29:25.660
going to be anywhere
near the money.

00:29:25.660 --> 00:29:27.910
I don't really make
decisions based on that.

00:29:27.910 --> 00:29:29.250
I think the community doesn't.

00:29:29.250 --> 00:29:33.070
So it never really
caught on for anything.

00:29:33.070 --> 00:29:36.200
I've never actually
heard anyone use that.

00:29:36.200 --> 00:29:37.700
So he came up with
this thing called

00:29:37.700 --> 00:29:41.210
effective M, which
makes sense, if you

00:29:41.210 --> 00:29:43.350
look at M from his perspective.

00:29:43.350 --> 00:29:51.010
Effective M, it's your M
divided by-- you multiply by how

00:29:51.010 --> 00:29:52.870
shorthanded your table is.

00:29:52.870 --> 00:29:56.230
And it gives you the
equivalent of the number

00:29:56.230 --> 00:29:59.310
of 10-handed tables
you could survive.

00:29:59.310 --> 00:30:01.780
It just means that,
say you have 10 Ms,

00:30:01.780 --> 00:30:05.070
you could survive
10 rounds of blinds.

00:30:05.070 --> 00:30:07.020
If you have three
people at your table,

00:30:07.020 --> 00:30:09.950
you can't survive for
another like six hours

00:30:09.950 --> 00:30:12.630
because you actually pay
the blind every other hand.

00:30:12.630 --> 00:30:14.020
That's what
effective M is doing.

00:30:14.020 --> 00:30:17.780
It reduces your
M proportionally.

00:30:17.780 --> 00:30:21.420
Since he's looking at this
from the perspective of when

00:30:21.420 --> 00:30:25.780
you need to start making
moves, it kind of makes sense

00:30:25.780 --> 00:30:28.350
that your M would be reduced
if you're shorthanded.

00:30:28.350 --> 00:30:31.520
But I look at M from the
perspective of how valuable it

00:30:31.520 --> 00:30:33.950
is in terms of blinds.

00:30:33.950 --> 00:30:35.280
So I don't really use that.

00:30:35.280 --> 00:30:38.070
I don't know anyone who really
uses effective M either.

00:30:38.070 --> 00:30:41.276
But he invented them, and maybe
they'll catch on eventually.

00:30:41.276 --> 00:30:43.150
So I think that's going
to be done for today.

00:30:43.150 --> 00:30:46.140
Thanks, everyone, for
a good first lecture.

